s these programs compete for scarce resources, it is important to develop a clear view of their impact as tools for poverty alleviation. Targeting Investments in Children tackles the problem of evaluating these programs by examining them using a common metric: their impact on earnings in adulthood. The volume’s contributors explore a variety of issues, such as the effect of interventions targeted at children of different ages, and study a range of programs, including child care, after-school care, and drug prevention. The results will be invaluable to educational leaders and researchers as well as policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChild welfarexGovernment policyzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aFederal aid to child welfarezUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aPoor childrenxServices forzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  apoverty, poor, class, money, economics, political economy, politics, resources, investments, children, child, united states of america, usa, american society, government, governing, minority population, childhood, labor market, education, healthcare, health, alleviation, programs, incentives, services, policymakers, federal aid, evaluation, domestic policy, childcare, after-school care, drug prevention, economic assistance, development, vocational training, adolescence.1 aAnderson, Patricia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurdick-Will, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeming, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Greg J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDynarski, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct